<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="40" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1554,2016]" pageId="0" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,1554,1578]" pageId="0" pageNumber="40">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the new genus refers to its physiognomy which is very similar to the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Melichar" authorityName="Melichar" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pythamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1325,1436,1554,1578]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="40">Pythamus</emphasis>
Melichar
</taxonomicName>
externally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="41" pageId="0" pageNumber="40" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1554,2016]" pageId="0" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1625,1650]" pageId="0" pageNumber="40">Description.</emphasis>
Body medium sized. Head with apex arcuately produced, lateral margins strongly carinate, with median keel anterad of round elevated structure near midlength, submarginal carina mesad of ocellus. Vertex about as long as wide or slightly shorter than wide, about as long as pronotum and longer than scutellum. Ocellus located at side of submarginal carina. Face including eyes longer than wide. Frontoclypeus broad and swollen at base, with median longitudinal carina strongly elevated, laterally obliquely striate; lora reaching slightly beyond midlength of clypellus. Forewing veins slightly prominent, with R 
<number box="[755,761,1821,1835]" pageId="0" pageNumber="40" value="1.0">1</number>
a present; four apical cells present; crossvein m-cu 
<number box="[1338,1346,1821,1835]" pageId="0" pageNumber="40" value="2.0">2</number>
present and close to m-cu 
<number box="[351,359,1860,1874]" pageId="0" pageNumber="40" value="1.0">1</number>
, forming small discal cell; appendix very narrow. Pronotum broad, wider than head. Scutellum triangular, with transverse depression distinct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1554,2016]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1436,151,682]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="41" pageId="0" pageNumber="40">Male pygofer without ventral process. Subgenital plate elongate; macrosetae irregularly distributed distally, uniseriate in basal half; with row of setae along outboard submargin. Aedeagal shaft somewhat slender, tubular, with pair of lateral flanges near apex, recurved dorsally; gonopore apical. Style slender, elongate, with footlike apex of apophysis having elongated lateral angle. Connective Y-shaped with median anterior lobe, stem longer than arms.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,555,223,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,151,682]" box="[199,555,223,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,223,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,426,223,247]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">China</collectingCountry>
(Guizhou).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="41" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,151,682]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,260,284]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new genus is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Melichar" authorityName="Melichar" box="[699,917,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pythamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[699,809,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Pythamus</emphasis>
Melichar
</taxonomicName>
externally, but may be distinguished from the latter by: 
<number box="[261,273,295,319]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="1.0">1</number>
) white markings of forewing scattered (
<figureCitation box="[736,806,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1869,1892]" captionTargetBox="[192,1386,227,1772]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,195,1815]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 9. Parapythamus suiyangensis sp. nov. 1. Head and thorax, dorsal view; 2. Head and thorax, lateral view; 3. Face; 4. Aedeagus and connective, ventral view; 5. Aedeagus and connective, lateral view; 6. style; 7. Subgenital plate; 8. Male pygofer, lateral view; 9. Forewing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">
Fig. 
<number box="[790,806,295,319]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
), with R 
<number box="[907,913,311,325]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="1.0">1</number>
a and small closed discal cell present; 
<number box="[1349,1364,295,319]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="2.0">2</number>
) male pygofer side without ventral process (
<figureCitation box="[576,644,335,359]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1869,1892]" captionTargetBox="[192,1386,227,1772]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,195,1815]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 9. Parapythamus suiyangensis sp. nov. 1. Head and thorax, dorsal view; 2. Head and thorax, lateral view; 3. Face; 4. Aedeagus and connective, ventral view; 5. Aedeagus and connective, lateral view; 6. style; 7. Subgenital plate; 8. Male pygofer, lateral view; 9. Forewing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">
Fig. 
<number box="[629,644,335,359]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
); 
<number box="[667,681,335,359]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="3.0">3</number>
) vertex about as long as wide or slightly shorter than wide (
<figureCitation box="[1358,1429,335,359]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1869,1892]" captionTargetBox="[192,1386,227,1772]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,195,1815]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 9. Parapythamus suiyangensis sp. nov. 1. Head and thorax, dorsal view; 2. Head and thorax, lateral view; 3. Face; 4. Aedeagus and connective, ventral view; 5. Aedeagus and connective, lateral view; 6. style; 7. Subgenital plate; 8. Male pygofer, lateral view; 9. Forewing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">
Figs 
<number box="[1415,1429,335,359]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="1.1">1</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,182,370,394]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1859,1882]" captionTargetBox="[198,1436,225,1791]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1835]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 11. Parapythamus suiyangensis sp. nov. 10. dorsal view; 11. lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201603/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">10</figureCitation>
), unlike the vertex of 
<taxonomicName box="[428,538,371,395]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pythamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[428,538,371,395]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Pythamus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which is distinctly longer than wide. The new genus is also similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[1328,1429,371,395]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Cunedda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1328,1429,371,395]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Cunedda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but has the vertex shorter than the pronotum (longer in 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant, 1918" authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1918" box="[769,1055,407,431]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Cunedda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[769,870,407,431]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Cunedda</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Distant" box="[877,1055,407,431]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" refString="Distant, W. L. (1918) The Fauna of British India including Ceylon and Burma. Rhynchota. Volume VII. Homoptera: Appendix. Heteroptera: Addenda. Taylor &amp; Francis, London. 210 pp." type="book" year="1918">
(Distant, 
<number box="[981,1037,407,431]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="1918.0">1918</number>
))
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and the aedeagal shaft more slen- der, tubular, and with a pair of lateral preapical flanges (
<figureCitation box="[778,879,442,466]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1869,1892]" captionTargetBox="[192,1386,227,1772]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,195,1815]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 9. Parapythamus suiyangensis sp. nov. 1. Head and thorax, dorsal view; 2. Head and thorax, lateral view; 3. Face; 4. Aedeagus and connective, ventral view; 5. Aedeagus and connective, lateral view; 6. style; 7. Subgenital plate; 8. Male pygofer, lateral view; 9. Forewing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">
Figs 
<number box="[835,879,442,466]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="4.5">4, 5</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,151,682]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Viraktamath" box="[352,675,479,503]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" refString="Viraktamath, C. A. &amp; Webb, M. D. (2007) Review of the leafhopper genus Pythamus Melichar (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Evacanthinae) in the Indian subcontinent. Zootaxa, 1546, 51 - 61." type="journal article" year="2007">
Viraktamath &amp; Webb (
<number box="[606,667,479,503]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="2007.0">2007</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[686,797,479,503]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pythamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[686,797,479,503]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Pythamus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a ventral process on the male pygofer. Thus, the species 
<taxonomicName authority="Huang (Huang, 1992)" authorityName="Huang (Huang" authorityYear="1992" box="[202,737,514,539]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pythamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chiabaotawow">
<emphasis box="[202,482,515,539]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Pythamus chiabaotawow</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[489,737,514,539]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" refString="Huang, K. W. (1992) Taxonomy of Evacanthini of Taiwan (Homoptera: Cicadellidae: Cicadellinae). Bulletin of National Museum of Natural Science, 3, 159 - 185." type="journal article">
Huang (Huang, 
<number box="[669,729,514,538]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="1992.0">1992</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Zhang (Li &amp; Zhang, 1993)" authorityName="Li &amp; Zhang (Li &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="1993" box="[749,1253,514,539]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pythamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis box="[749,886,516,539]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">P. punctatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[892,1253,514,538]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" refString="Li, Z. Z. &amp; Zhang, Y. L. (1993) Two new species of Evacanthinae from China (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Journal of Guizhou Aguicultural College. 12 (Suppl.), 23 - 26." type="journal article">
Li &amp; Zhang (Li &amp; Zhang, 
<number box="[1188,1245,514,538]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="1993.0">1993</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Wang (Li &amp; Wang, 2006)" authorityName="Li &amp; Wang (Li &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pythamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyalipictatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">P. hyalipictatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[216,584,551,576]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" refString="Li, Z. Z. &amp; Wang, L. M. (2006) Cicadellidae: Evacanthinae, Nervaninae, Coelidiinae, Iassinae and Euscelinae. In: Li &amp; Jin, Incects from Fanjingshan Landscape. Guizhou Science and Technology Publishing House, Guiyang, China. 162 - 189." type="book chapter">
Li 
<emphasis box="[251,273,552,575]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">&amp;</emphasis>
Wang (Li 
<emphasis box="[404,426,552,575]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">&amp;</emphasis>
Wang, 
<number box="[518,576,551,575]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="2006.0">2006</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
are incorrectly placed in this genus. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Ramakrishnan" box="[1182,1431,551,575]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" refString="Ramakrishnan, U. (1989) New leafhopper species of Dussana Distant and male genitalia of Cunedda phaeops Distant (Evacanthinae: Cicadellidae: Homoptera). Journal of Entomological Research, New Delhi, 12, 45 - 50." type="journal article" year="1989">
Ramakrishnan (
<number box="[1363,1423,551,575]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="1989.0">1989</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[151,252,587,611]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Cunedda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,252,587,611]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Cunedda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also lacks a ventral process on the male pygofer. Because the species of 
<emphasis box="[1112,1213,587,611]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Cudedda</emphasis>
described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Li" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" refString="Li, Z. Z. &amp; Wang, L. M. (1996) The Evacanthinae (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae) of China. Guizhou Technology Publishing Company, Guiyang, China. 134 pp." type="book" year="1996">
Li &amp; Webb (
<number box="[230,289,623,647]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" value="1996.0">1996</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
have a ventral process on male pygofer, they also should be placed elsewhere. We will treat these species in another paper.
</paragraph>
